item.title: CRS-23 Dragon Undocking
item.description: The SpaceX CRS-23 Dragon spacecraft will undock from the International Space Station ahead of its reentry, splashdown and recovery.

item.title: Russian EVA-50
item.description: Roscosmos cosmonauts Oleg Novitskiy and Pyotr Dubrov will exit the International Space Station through the Poisk airlock to continue establishing external cable connections between the new MLM Nauka module and the Zvezda module.

item.title: Russian EVA-49
item.description: Roscosmos cosmonauts Oleg Novitskiy and Pyotr Dubrov will exit the International Space Station through the Poisk airlock to establish external cable connections between the new MLM Nauka module and the Zvezda module.

item.title: CRS-23 Dragon Docking
item.description: Following its launch atop a Falcon 9, the CRS-23 Dragon will autonomously dock to the ISS, bringing crew supplies as well as experiments.

item.title: Falcon 9 Block 5 | Dragon CRS-2 SpX-23
item.description:
SpaceX will launch the cargo variant of its Dragon 2 spacecraft on their 23rd commercial resupply services mission to the International Space Station. The flight will be conducted under the second Commercial Resupply Services contract with NASA.
Dragon will be filled with supplies and payloads, including critical materials to directly support science and research investigations that occur onboard the orbiting laboratory.

item.title: US EVA-77
item.description: NASA astronaut Mark Vande Hei and JAXA astronaut Akihiko Hoshide will venture outside the orbiting outpost to perform maintenance tasks and activate the Bartolomeo platform on the exterior of the Columbus module.

item.title: Soyuz 2.1b/Fregat-M | OneWeb 9
item.description: A batch of 34 satellites for the OneWeb satellite constellation, which is intended to provide global Internet broadband service for individual consumers. The constellation is planned to have around 648 microsatellites (of which 60 are spares), around 150 kg each, operating in Ku-band from low Earth orbit.

item.title: Vega | Pléiades Neo 4
item.description: Pléiades Neo is a constellation of four optical high-resolution Earth observation satellites built and operated by Airbus. It is a dual purpose constellation, serving both civilian and military purposes. Pléiades Neo 4 is the second satellite in the constellation which is to deliver imagery with spatial resolution of 30 cm. It is launched along with several rideshare payloads.
